# eRPC multi-provider proxy for Optimism mainnet (chain 10).
#
# **Current shape: 2-of-3 consensus across validationcloud + nodies + tenderly.**
#
# Iteration history:
#  - #130 deploy: tried publicnode + official-op + ankr-op. official-op
#    (mainnet.optimism.io) → HTTP 429 from Mac mini IP. ankr-op needs
#    paid API key. Dropped both, swapped in tenderly + 1rpc.
#  - #138 deploy: publicnode + tenderly + 1rpc (2-of-3, threshold=2).
#  - #144 deploy: bumped to 3-of-3 after Codex retro-audit caught the
#    CF-collusion poisoning attack (2 CF-fronted upstreams returning
#    the same forged view satisfy quorum 2-of-3 → poison authoritative).
#  - **2026-05-20 (this PR)**: dropped 1rpc-op entirely. eRPC's URL
#    parser strips the `/op` path segment from `https://1rpc.io/op`,
#    sending requests to 1rpc's landing page instead of the OP RPC.
#    Confirmed via the parsed-config dump:
#      "endpoint":"https://1rpc.io#redacted=..." (no path)
#    1rpc consistently failed → `n/a = ErrUpstreamsExhausted` on every
#    consensus call → 3-of-3 was unsatisfiable → driver couldn't boot.
#
# **Final config: 3 upstreams, agreementThreshold=2 (2-of-3 quorum).**
# 2026-07-23 keyed migration: replaced the free publicnode(Cloudflare) + dead
# self-host(100.77.53.81) with two KEYED providers after a free-tier-429 outage
# (tenderly's keyless gateway 429'd under load, amplified by the dead self-node's
# 8s participant timeout, collapsing the quorum).
# 2026-07-24: swapped the keyed blockdaemon-op → free no-key nodies-op (BD's
# free-tier burst cap was exhausted, freezing its head ~13.6h; not upgrading BD).
# This leaves only ONE keyed provider (validationcloud) — see the availability
# note below. See the per-upstream comments in the `upstreams:` block for the full
# rationale. This header is the top-level summary.
#
#   validationcloud-op  mainnet.optimism.validationcloud.io  Validation Cloud
#                                                             CDN: istio-envoy (NON-Cloudflare)
#                                                             auth: KEYED (URL path)
#   nodies-op           op-pokt.nodies.app                   Nodies / POKT
#                                                             CDN: Cloudflare
#                                                             auth: NONE (free public tier)
#   tenderly-op         optimism.gateway.tenderly.co         Tenderly
#                                                             DNS: Google Cloud, free public tier
#
# **Threat model — 2-of-3 over 3 distinct failure domains, with the hard
# invariant that AT MOST ONE upstream is Cloudflare-fronted (nodies):**
#
#  - Cloudflare compromise → only nodies is hijacked. validationcloud
#    (istio / non-CF) and tenderly (Google DNS) return the real answer →
#    dispute → returnError → driver does NOT settle against forged state.
#  - Validation Cloud OR Tenderly/Google compromise → the other two form
#    quorum on the real answer → safe. NO 2-upstream subset shares one
#    CDN/DNS, so a single-provider compromise can never satisfy quorum alone.
#  - Two independent failure domains compromised at once: nation-state class,
#    out of scope.
#  - All three returning the same answer IS the canonical chain state
#    (independent operators agreeing on block data is the correct case).
#
# Availability: 2 of 3 must both respond AND agree; a single-upstream blip is
# tolerated (the other two form quorum). Fail-closed below quorum:
# lowParticipantsBehavior:returnError → driver pauses rather than settling on
# unverified state. Trade-off accepted: "rather not settle than settle against
# forged state." Standard posture for any DEX moving real money.
#
# Rationale (replace-not-expand): N=3 keeps the 2-of-3 invariant defensible;
# expanding N>3 under eRPC's random sampling (maxParticipants:3) would silently
# weaken the model to "attacker needs ≥2 of N".
#
# **Availability note (2026-07-24):** only ONE upstream is now KEYED
# (validationcloud); nodies and tenderly are both FREE public tiers. A correlated
# free-tier rate-limit hitting BOTH under a load spike would leave only
# validationcloud → below quorum → lowParticipants:returnError (driver pauses,
# safe but unavailable). Accepted regression from the prior two-keyed backbone:
# blockdaemon's keyed endpoint was itself rate-limited to death (a dead backbone,
# not a reliable one), so nodies is a net availability GAIN (3 working upstreams
# vs the effective 2-of-2 a frozen BD left). If OP order-flow grows, restore a
# two-keyed backbone by putting a keyed free-tier provider (Chainstack / BlastAPI /
# Infura) in place of a free lane. nodies verified clean on eth_call + getBalance +
# getLogs + a 15-call burst 2026-07-24.
#
# Per-block consensus equality is sound on OP: post-Bedrock block contents are
# deterministic per L2 block number; only tip drift on "latest" varies, handled
# by `enforceHighestBlock`.
#
# Endpoint exposed: http://rpc-proxy:4000/main/evm/10

logLevel: warn  # was info; info logs 1 line/RPC req+resp -> filled the docker-VM disk (2026-06-15 incident). warn still surfaces consensus disputes / upstream-exhausted.

projects:
  - id: main

    networks:
      - architecture: evm
        evm:
          chainId: 10
          integrity:
            enforceHighestBlock: true
            enforceNonNullTaggedBlocks: true
        # Consensus failsafe: defeats fork-view-poisoning on state-reads.
        # Each free provider is unauthenticated HTTPS — a hostile provider
        # (or MITM via CA compromise / DNS hijack) could otherwise serve a
        # self-consistent fork that the autopilot signs settlements against.
        # 2-of-3 agreement on the methods that drive solver behavior closes
        # that hole.
        failsafe:
          # Critical reads: state-dependent calls that gate solver behavior
          # and settlement validity. eth_getTransactionByHash is included
          # because the response carries forkable fields (blockHash,
          # blockNumber); a hostile upstream on the non-consensus "*" path
          # could otherwise mislead the autopilot's settlement-watcher.
          # Network-level timeout 12s gives 2s headroom over the slowest
          # upstream-level timeout (~10s) — sharp-edges follow-up #6.
          #
          # Method list (Codex retro-audit, 2026-05-20):
          # - `eth_estimateGas`: a forged-low estimate yields txs that
          #   revert (gas-only loss bounded by the 5 gwei cap from #131,
          #   but still budget-wasteful).
          # - `eth_feeHistory`: feeds into EIP-1559 fee predictions;
          #   manipulation lets a hostile upstream steer submission gas.
          #
          # 2026-05-20 evening — DROPPED `eth_getBlockByNumber` and
          # `eth_getBlockByHash` from strict consensus. They were the
          # dominant source of `ErrConsensusDispute` (95+ disputes in
          # 2-minute windows post-deploy) because the two upstreams hold
          # slightly different views of `"latest"` at any wall-clock
          # microsecond — pure tip-drift, no security signal. Block reads
          # by NUMBER (not tag) would be deterministic but the driver
          # mostly queries `"latest"`. Removing these methods from
          # consensus drops to the `*` catch-all rule below (retry, no
          # consensus). Per-block-content integrity is still enforced
          # via `enforceHighestBlock: true` + `enforceNonNullTaggedBlocks:
          # true` at the network level above. Settlement-integrity
          # methods (`eth_call`, `eth_getLogs`, `eth_getTransactionReceipt`,
          # `eth_getTransactionByHash`) keep 2-of-3 consensus.
          #
          # 2026-05-20 evening (2) — DROPPED `eth_getBalance` from strict
          # consensus too. Tenderly's free public Gateway hit per-IP
          # rate-limit (HTTP 429 ErrEndpointCapacityExceeded) under
          # sustained polling from driver+orderbook+autopilot. (Residual
          # since closed in 2026-05-20 evening (3) below.)
          #
          # 2026-05-20 evening (3) — ADDED self-hosted ophis-self-op
          # as the 3rd upstream. A self-hosted full node reached via
          # Tailscale, fully synced, controlled by us. This removes the
          # Tenderly rate-limit bottleneck (we poll our own node freely)
          # AND adds a 3rd fully-independent failure domain (separate
          # network operator — not CF, not Google).
          #
          # Restored: `eth_getBalance` back to strict consensus. The
          # rate-limit reason for demotion is no longer a constraint.
          #
          # Bumped: agreementThreshold 2 → 3 (every upstream must agree).
          # Threat model now (3 distinct DNS/operator/network):
          #   - CF DNS compromise: hijacks only publicnode → tenderly +
          #     self return truth → dispute → returnError → safe
          #   - Google DNS compromise: hijacks only tenderly → publicnode
          #     + self → safe
          #   - Aleph compromise (someone gets into our VM): hijacks only
          #     self → publicnode + tenderly → safe
          #   - All 3 simultaneously: requires owning CF + Google + Aleph
          #     infrastructures → nation-state++ class, out of scope.
          #
          # This is the strongest posture achievable today. The CF-DNS
          # concentration residual (documented through #144→#148 iterations)
          # is now fully closed.
          # 2026-05-20 — root-cause REVISED during task #112 investigation.
          # The Phase 3.1 swap failure was NOT a container→Tailscale
          # reachability issue (a one-shot alpine container on the same
          # docker network successfully called the self-hosted endpoint). The
          # actual cause: eRPC's punishMisbehavior policy was kicking the
          # self-hosted upstream into a 5-min sit-out every time it had
          # minor tip-drift (5 disputes in 10min → punishment). With OP's
          # 2s block time, tip-drift between independently-operated
          # indexers is the natural state — disputeThreshold:5 punishes
          # normal operation.
          #
          # ============================================================
          # 2026-05-20 (task #119) — SPLIT disputeThreshold BY METHOD.
          # ============================================================
          #
          # Why the single-bucket threshold:100 was unsafe to keep:
          # a single global threshold of 100 means a hostile upstream
          # can return up to 99 forged answers per 10-min window on the
          # most security-critical methods (eth_call, eth_getBalance)
          # before catching a 5-min sit-out — sustained ~95% DoS duty
          # cycle on the path that gates settlement. Phase 4 audit N1
          # (Codex + sharp-edges, 2026-05-20) flagged this as
          # defense-in-depth-required pre-meaningful-TVL.
          #
          # Split into two consensus blocks by threat surface:
          #
          # **Block A — deterministic-state methods (LOW threshold)**:
          # eth_call, eth_getBalance, eth_getCode, eth_getStorageAt.
          # These are pure state lookups at a specified block tag.
          #
          # `enforceHighestBlock: true` (set at the network level above)
          # gates routing to only-fully-caught-up upstreams — it does
          # NOT coordinate the participants to query a specific block
          # number. Two upstreams 1 block apart on "latest" will still
          # return two state snapshots; only the behind-tip one gets
          # routed-around. Drift IS real on this bucket.
          # `eth_getTransactionCount` is deliberately NOT in Block A:
          # the `pending` block tag is mempool-dependent, and the
          # driver's submission mempool is pinned to publicnode-op
          # alone — the self-hosted op-node will not see pending txs
          # before the sequencer gossips them back, so EIP-7702
          # delegation-setup ceremonies (90s of pending-tag polling)
          # would cordon self-hosted within seconds of every boot.
          # Moved to Block B where threshold:100 absorbs that burst.
          #
          # threshold:60 catches hostile sustained divergence ~1.7× faster
          # than the previous threshold:100 while preserving 3× headroom
          # over the live ~20 disputes/10min baseline (driven primarily
          # by ophis-self-op tip-drift on "latest" tags). Sharp-
          # edges finding 1 (2026-05-20): the 1.5× headroom of threshold:30
          # was insufficient for bootstrap-burst + OP-sequencer-hiccup
          # scenarios where all 3 upstreams snap back to consensus at
          # different microseconds. Threshold:60 is the floor; raise to
          # 100 (and accept the DoS-window cost) only if false-ejection
          # alerts fire repeatedly on a healthy upstream over a 24h
          # window.
          #
          # **Block B — tip-lag-tolerant observation methods (HIGH
          # threshold)**: eth_getLogs, eth_getTransactionReceipt,
          # eth_getTransactionByHash, eth_estimateGas, eth_feeHistory,
          # eth_getTransactionCount.
          # These have natural disagreement floors driven by indexer
          # propagation lag near the chain tip (e.g. just-landed
          # Settlement txs may not be indexed by all upstreams
          # simultaneously; estimateGas has provider-implementation
          # variance; feeHistory percentiles differ slightly between
          # providers; getTransactionCount with `pending` tag is
          # mempool-dependent and only the publicnode-op mempool is
          # authoritative for our submission path). threshold:100
          # absorbs this baseline drift while still catching sustained
          # malicious answers — each forged dispute still triggers
          # consensus failure → returnError → driver fails closed at
          # request time. The threshold only controls whether we keep
          # retrying that upstream over time.
          #
          # **Block C** is the existing catch-all retry (no consensus).
          #
          # Empirical baseline (live OP mainnet eRPC, ~1h window
          # 2026-05-20 evening):
          #   eth_call:                      2.09% dispute rate
          #   eth_feeHistory:                1.64% dispute rate
          #   eth_getTransactionReceipt:     0.25% dispute rate
          #   eth_getLogs:                   0.12% dispute rate
          # The Block A threshold of 60 leaves 3× headroom for eth_call
          # (the most-disputed method in that bucket). Operational reality
          # test: redeploy → monitor erpc_upstream_cordoned for false
          # ejections in the first hour. If false-ejection fires more
          # than once per 30 minutes on a healthy upstream, raise to 100
          # (matching Block B) and accept the DoS-window cost.
          #
          # **Pairs with new Prometheus alerts** (observability/alerts.yml):
          # - OphisOpErpcUpstreamCordoned (per-upstream sat-out detection)
          # - OphisOpErpcUpstreamBlockHeadLagging (chronic-lag root cause)
          # - OphisOpErpcCordonMetricAbsent (silent-monitoring-gap guard)

          # === Block A: Deterministic-state methods (LOW threshold) ===
          - matchMethod: "eth_call|eth_getBalance|eth_getCode|eth_getStorageAt"
            timeout:
              duration: 12s
            consensus:
              maxParticipants: 3
              # 2-of-3 across fully-independent failure domains:
              # - publicnode-op (Allnodes; CF DNS)
              # - tenderly-op (Tenderly; Google Cloud DNS)
              # - ophis-self-op (Aleph VM, self-hosted via Tailscale)
              agreementThreshold: 2
              # Tip-drift fix (#476): on OP's ~2s blocks publicnode + self
              # frequently sit 1 block apart on `latest`-tagged reads — a
              # DISPUTE (both upstreams UP, values disagree) that the old
              # returnError failed ~30-50% of the time. preferBlockHeadLeader
              # breaks the tie by freshest block; it still requires the
              # participants to have responded, so it is not a 1-of-N bypass.
              disputeBehavior: preferBlockHeadLeader
              # lowParticipants stays FAIL-CLOSED (Codex #476 P1): when fewer
              # than agreementThreshold upstreams return a valid response (an
              # outage, not a disagreement), refuse rather than serve the
              # lone freshest 1-of-3 — a single hijacked/stale fresh upstream
              # must never supply settlement/quote state unchecked.
              lowParticipantsBehavior: returnError
              # No `ignoreFields` here — see HL eRPC Codex Cyber finding #1.
              # Allowing field-level skip lets a hostile upstream forge the
              # skipped field while matching every other field; consensus
              # passes spuriously.
              punishMisbehavior:
                # TIGHT threshold for security-critical state lookups.
                # 3× headroom over the empirical 20 disputes/10min
                # baseline on eth_call. A hostile upstream catches a 5-min
                # sit-out after 60 forged answers (vs 100 in the old
                # single-bucket config) — 1.7× DoS-window reduction on
                # the settlement-gating path. Sharp-edges (2026-05-20)
                # bumped this from 30 → 60 to absorb bootstrap-burst
                # scenarios where 3 upstreams snap back to consensus at
                # different microseconds during driver redeploy.
                disputeThreshold: 60
                disputeWindow: 10m
                sitOutPenalty: 5m

          # === Block B: Tip-lag-sensitive observation methods (HIGH threshold) ===
          #
          # 2026-05-21 follow-up: REMOVED eth_getTransactionReceipt from
          # the Block B consensus regex. The 200-threshold bump on 2026-05-20
          # was not enough — `OphisOpErpcUpstreamCordoned` fired 3 more
          # times within hours of the deploy, each time accumulating
          # ~12,000 `response_type="empty"` misbehavior events on
          # ophis-self-op before the eviction. Root cause is
          # structural: op-reth's receipt indexing is materially slower
          # than publicnode + tenderly's hosted indexers (likely they
          # serve from a denormalized receipt cache rather than
          # re-traversing the trie). During Settlement-broadcast bursts
          # the driver polls fresh receipts every block tick; self-hosted
          # returns empty for a few seconds longer than the others, ends
          # up the lone dissenter on every poll, and the dispute counter
          # accumulates faster than ANY threshold we could tune around
          # without effectively disabling the policy.
          #
          # Trade-off accepted: eth_getTransactionReceipt now falls
          # through to Block C (catch-all retry, no consensus). The
          # protection we lose is "a hostile upstream forging
          # receipt-exists/receipt-missing to mislead the autopilot
          # settlement-watcher". The watcher cross-checks via eth_call
          # against the on-chain Settlement contract (which IS still
          # under Block A consensus at threshold:60), so a forged
          # receipt alone cannot cause settlement-state divergence —
          # only the eth_call against Settlement's `filledAmount` is
          # authoritative. Receipt confirmation is best-effort UX, not
          # a security primitive.
          #
          # If a future version of op-reth speeds up receipt indexing
          # (or we switch to op-erigon / op-geth on the VM), re-add
          # eth_getTransactionReceipt to this regex and bump back.
          - matchMethod: "eth_getLogs|eth_getTransactionByHash|eth_estimateGas|eth_feeHistory|eth_getTransactionCount"
            timeout:
              duration: 12s
            consensus:
              maxParticipants: 3
              agreementThreshold: 2
              # Same tip-drift posture as Block A: dispute breaks ties by
              # freshest block, but lowParticipants stays fail-closed so an
              # outage never downgrades to 1-of-3 (Codex #476 P1).
              disputeBehavior: preferBlockHeadLeader
              lowParticipantsBehavior: returnError
              punishMisbehavior:
                # 200 was sized to absorb the receipt burst — without
                # that method here, the remaining members have much
                # lower dispute floors, but we keep 100 (the original
                # value) as a defensive cap. Drift between publicnode +
                # tenderly + self on `eth_getLogs` near tip is ~10
                # disputes / 10min historically; threshold:100 gives 10×
                # headroom.
                disputeThreshold: 100
                disputeWindow: 10m
                sitOutPenalty: 5m

          # === eth_getTransactionReceipt: consensus WITHOUT punishMisbehavior ===
          # Settlement-authoritative — the driver derives Executed/Reverted from
          # this receipt (driver/domain/mempools.rs), so a single forged/hidden
          # receipt could poison the settle() outcome. It needs 2-of-3 agreement.
          # BUT it gets its OWN rule with NO punishMisbehavior: the self-hosted
          # op-reth returns empty receipts a few seconds longer than the hosted
          # indexers during settlement broadcast, so under the punished Block A/B
          # rules it disputed -> cordoned ophis-self-op (Codex #465/#466, ~12k
          # empty-misbehavior events). With no punishment the lag merely yields a
          # transient returnError, which the driver treats as Pending and keeps
          # polling (fail-safe: it can delay confirmation but never accept a
          # forged receipt or evict the node). Once the node's receipt lag is
          # fixed (op-erigon/op-geth), fold this into a punished block.
          - matchMethod: "eth_getTransactionReceipt"
            timeout:
              duration: 12s
            consensus:
              maxParticipants: 3
              agreementThreshold: 2
              disputeBehavior: returnError
              lowParticipantsBehavior: returnError

          # === Block C: Catch-all retry (no consensus) ===
          # Block-stream polling, balance reads on non-consensus paths.
          # Tx submission routes via driver's pinned [[submission.mempool]]
          # block (single endpoint, nonce-coherent).
          - matchMethod: "*"
            timeout:
              duration: 12s
            retry:
              maxAttempts: 3
              delay: 150ms
              backoffMaxDelay: 1s
              backoffFactor: 1.5
              jitter: 50ms

    # OP block time is ~2s post-Bedrock; align tip-block tracking.
    upstreamDefaults:
      evm:
        statePollerInterval: 5s
        statePollerDebounce: 1s

    upstreams:
      # ─── Consensus backbone (2026-07-23 keyed migration; 2026-07-24 nodies swap) ───
      # The 2026-07-23 outage was free-tier fragility — Tenderly's keyless gateway
      # 429'd under load and collapsed the quorum (publicnode alone < threshold=2).
      # publicnode was DROPPED (not kept as a 4th) because it is Cloudflare-fronted:
      # two CF upstreams in a 2-of-3 could be poisoned identically by a single CDN
      # compromise and satisfy quorum. Invariant = ≤1 CF-fronted upstream per quorum.
      # Validation Cloud (istio-envoy / own infra, non-CF) supplies the CDN diversity.
      # 2026-07-24: keyed blockdaemon-op (CF, rate-limited to death) → free no-key
      # nodies-op (CF) — like-for-like on the ≤1-CF invariant (nodies is now the sole
      # CF lane), but it leaves only ONE keyed provider; see the header availability note.
      # Hosts are LITERAL (so the CI fail-closed guard's urlsplit can pin the failure
      # domain); the keyed provider's secret KEY resolves from .env
      # (${VALIDATIONCLOUD_OP_KEY}) via render-configs.sh envsubst — NEVER committed.
      # Key arrived via chat 2026-07-23 → rotate on next maintenance window.
      # (BLOCKDAEMON_OP_KEY is now unused; nodies takes no auth.)
      - id: validationcloud-op
        # Keyed, non-CF (istio-envoy). The CDN-diverse anchor + the sole KEYED lane.
        endpoint: https://mainnet.optimism.validationcloud.io/v1/${VALIDATIONCLOUD_OP_KEY}
        failsafe:
          - matchMethod: "*"
            timeout:
              duration: 8s
            retry:
              maxAttempts: 3
              delay: 200ms
              backoffMaxDelay: 1s
              backoffFactor: 1.5
              jitter: 50ms

      - id: nodies-op
        # Free, no-key, Cloudflare-fronted — the ONE permitted CF upstream in this quorum
        # (replaced keyed blockdaemon-op 2026-07-24: BD's free-tier burst cap was exhausted,
        # freezing its head ~13.6h so it contributed nothing to consensus, and we are not
        # upgrading the BD tier). Nodies/POKT public OP gateway; verified eth_call +
        # eth_getBalance + eth_getLogs(10 blk, 2981 logs) + a 15-call burst (0 errors) at
        # the live head 2026-07-24. No auth form needed (eRPC's closed-world guard forbids
        # custom auth headers, and this endpoint takes none).
        endpoint: https://op-pokt.nodies.app
        failsafe:
          - matchMethod: "*"
            timeout:
              duration: 8s
            retry:
              maxAttempts: 3
              delay: 200ms
              backoffMaxDelay: 1s
              backoffFactor: 1.5
              jitter: 50ms

      - id: tenderly-op
        # Non-CF anchor (Google Cloud DNS). Tenderly's public gateway
        # has no documented rate cap; we measured ~270ms first-byte
        # which is comfortable headroom. If Tenderly tightens this
        # endpoint behind a key in the future, swap-procedure is in
        # docs/operations/op-erpc-runbook.md.
        endpoint: https://optimism.gateway.tenderly.co
        failsafe:
          - matchMethod: "*"
            timeout:
              duration: 8s
            retry:
              maxAttempts: 3
              delay: 200ms
              backoffMaxDelay: 1s
              backoffFactor: 1.5
              jitter: 50ms

      # ─── Consensus set (2026-07-24): validationcloud + nodies + tenderly ───
      # 2-of-3, agreementThreshold=2, maxParticipants=3. validationcloud (istio non-CF)
      # is the sole KEYED lane; nodies (CF) and tenderly (Google DNS) are both FREE
      # public tiers. Exactly one CF-fronted upstream (nodies) → a single-CDN compromise
      # can't poison a full quorum. Supersedes the free 2-of-2 (publicnode+tenderly), the
      # dead self-host, AND the frozen keyed blockdaemon-op (rate-limited to death 07-24).
      # AVAILABILITY WARNING: with only one keyed lane, a correlated free-tier 429 on BOTH
      # nodies AND tenderly under a load spike drops to validationcloud-only → below
      # quorum → fail-closed (driver pauses). Restore a two-keyed backbone (add a keyed
      # free-tier provider in place of a free lane) if OP order-flow grows. See header.
      #
      # #841 self-host (46.255.204.207, op-reth) is now OPTIONAL, not load-bearing. If
      # re-added, keep the ≤1-CF-per-quorum invariant and either swap a lane (stay at 3)
      # or bump to 2-of-4 — the latter ALSO needs assert-erpc-failclosed.py's
      # EXPECTED_UPSTREAMS + EXPECTED_UPSTREAM_HOSTS updated. drpc/meowrpc/omnia remain
      # disqualified (all Cloudflare-fronted → a 2-CF quorum defeats the fork-poisoning
      # threat model).

